aws::graph::propositions: # Aviation Accident Report for Cessna P206 in Key West, Florida
The accident occurred in Key West, Florida.
The accident occurred on January 3, 2015.
The accident occurred at 10:15 Local time.
The aircraft involved was a Cessna P206.
The defining event was loss of engine power (total).
The flight was conducted under Part 135: Air taxi & commuter - Non-scheduled.
The accident number was ERA15LA090.
The aircraft registration was N2534X.
The aircraft sustained substantial damage.
The accident resulted in 4 minor injuries.
The accident resulted in 2 people with no injuries.
The pilot reported the airplane was about 300 ft above the ground when the engine quit.
The airplane was on final approach when the engine quit.
The engine quit suddenly with no surging or other warning signs.
The pilot selected the auxiliary fuel pump to the high position.
The pilot switched fuel tanks.
The engine came back to life momentarily after the pilot's actions.
The engine quit again after momentarily coming back to life.
The airplane was unable to reach the runway.
The pilot made a forced landing in a lagoon.
The lagoon was about 1/4 mile short of the runway.
The right wing sustained structural damage during the forced landing.
Examination of the fuel system revealed the right fuel tank was full.
Examination of the fuel system revealed the left fuel tank had 15 gallons of fuel remaining.
Evidence of fuel was noted in the lines from the fuel tanks to the fuel manifold valve.
Internal engine continuity was confirmed during examination.
Compression and suction were observed on all of the cylinders.
The spark plug electrodes were normal in appearance.
The engine-driven fuel pump was tested.
The magnetos were tested.
No evidence of a preexisting malfunction was found.
The reason for the loss of engine power could not be determined.
The National Transportation Safety Board determined the probable cause of this accident to be a total loss of engine power.
The reasons for the total loss of engine power could not be determined during postaccident examinations and testing.

text:
# Aviation Investigation Final Report

## Location:
Key West, Florida

## Date & Time: 
January 3, 2015, 10:15 Local

## Aircraft:
Cessna P206

## Defining Event:
Loss of engine power (total)

## Flight Conducted Under:
Part 135: Air taxi & commuter - Non-scheduled

## Accident Number:
ERA15LA090

## Registration:
N2534X

## Aircraft Damage:
Substantial

## Injuries:
4 Minor, 2 None

## Analysis

The pilot reported that the airplane was about 300 ft above the ground and on final approach when the engine "quit suddenly with no surging or other warning signs." He selected the auxiliary fuel pump to the high position and switched fuel tanks. The pilot stated that the engine "came back to life momentarily and then quit again." The airplane was unable to reach the runway, and the pilot made a forced landing in a lagoon about 1/4 mile short of the runway, during which the right wing sustained structural damage.

Examination of the fuel system revealed that the right fuel tank was full and that the left fuel tank had 15 gallons of fuel remaining. Evidence of fuel was also noted in the lines from the fuel tanks to the fuel manifold valve. Internal engine continuity was confirmed, and compression and suction were observed on all of the cylinders. The spark plug electrodes were normal in appearance. The engine-driven fuel pump and magnetos were tested, and no evidence of a preexisting malfunction was found. The reason for the loss of engine power could not be determined.

## Probable Cause and Findings

The National Transportation Safety Board determines the probable cause(s) of this accident to be:

A total loss of engine power for reasons that could not be determined during postaccident examinations and testing.

---
